metadata.name: monopole #52
metadata.description:
Physics is, above all, beautiful.

Inspired by all the things I find beautiful in physics, and the nostalgia I feel for my undergraduate days of learning about the universe. I sought here to explore what can be created with simple graphics showing simple physical systems. 

The vector field shown is the field from a collection of monopoles, such as electrons and positrons or hypothetical magnetic monopoles.

The papers and inks available are those I have on my desk.

A 2400x2400 download of the image can be generated by pressing UP, but this will take several minutes. An SVG download can be made by pressing DOWN and is suitable for plotting (or laser cutting).

metadata.name: Intertwined #186
metadata.description:
Intertwined began as a study of how to overlap randomized shapes at many intersection points while retaining consistency and physical accuracy. I initially envisioned vines growing on buildings, but over time Intertwined moved in a more abstract embroidery-like direction while retaining influences from that foundational concept.

Controls:
Key S: Save the output as a jpeg at the current resolution (only available once the piece has finished loading).
Key Arrow Up: Scale the resolution up by a multiple of 1080 pixels. There is no maximum. The current highest recommended scale-factor is 4x.
Key Arrow Down: Scale the resolution down by a multiple of 1080 pixels. 1080p is the minimum.
Key A: Skip the construction animation to show the final result immediately (please note that for pieces with a larger grid skipping the animation may cause a long pause).

Browser Support: Confirmed to work in Chrome Version 97.0.4692.71

metadata.name: There And Then #55
metadata.description:
This project draws inspiration from the dynamic and exploratory ethos of Hic Et Nunc's early days, when artists were venturing into the possibilities of NFTs and pushing creative boundaries.

The color palettes were inadvertently provided by some talented artists who had originally intended them for another project, which was ultimately completed but never published.
Harvey McFly is to blame for the leak.

The color palettes have been paired together, creating an unexpected chromatic collaboration between the artists.

I have chosen to mint this project from TheWallet, as it represents one of the most intriguing experiments ever conducted on a blockchain.

This is the inaugural work to be published on fx(hash) through TheWallet, and I hope that other artists will follow suit and engage in this playful and nonsensical practice in the future.

A special thanks goes out to @TheWalletNft, who suggested the idea of minting on fx(hash) and handled the profile setup on the site.

The open and collaborative nature of TheWallet allows anyone with the seed phrase to modify the sale and to publish any kind of content from TheWallet. For this reason this profile is not, and should never be verified by fx(hash) and collectors should pay extra caution when collecting from it.

Yours, CCDDBB

Hand coded with love. üíö
Powered by p5 and chroma.

----------------------------------------------
TheWallet original post: https://typed.art/967

metadata.name: auras (scotomas from an auric migraine) #2
metadata.description:
auras (scotomas from an auric migraine)

have you ever had an auric migraine?

i have.

five exactly.

electric storms on my brain stem.

with pretty little floaters to obscure my vision.

this is my attempt to abstractly touch them.

such terrifyingly gorgeous creatures.

here -> you can have one too...

xo, 

shim sham*

*mouse click for a high pitch buzz for the migraine sensitivity to sound effect









origin story
in october 2019 shim sham her first auric migraine attack that included an episode of transient aphasia. known as a basilar or aural brain stem migraine, it creates an electrical storm at the base of the brain stem, which results in visual auras with blind spots (scotomas) sometimes outlined with geometric designs or zigzag lines that slowly float across your vision; shimmering stars. the onset sometimes begins with flashes of light, transient aphasia ~ speech difficulty, and the auric visions, followed by tingling in the hands and face, extreme pain, along with extreme sensitivity to sound and light, before, during and after the migraine. the post drome phase is the aftermath of the brainstorm and can last several days with an overall brain fog, dull headache pain, lethargy and sensitivity to sound and light. 

the aura is due to an electrical or chemical wave that moves across the brain. literally it is a brain storm. 

the auras that shim sham has seen are the most beautiful and terrifying apparitions ever experienced in waking life. in four years she's had 5. each one was different, beautiful and transformative. 

this an attempt at creating a visual and sonic abstraction to share with the world and acknowledge that some of us experience these things, each individually unique and wild.

concept originally inspired by "Depth sorting" by Jakub Valtar from processing 4 examples.

gratitude to joey zaza

made with p5.js and adapted from processing 4.

metadata.name: serendipity vs consequence #161
metadata.description:
This work is the result of a deterministic algorithm which manifests differently depending on the device it is viewed upon.  

The basis for the project is a phenomenon called z-fighting, a common issue in 3d graphics that appears when two or more objects overlap in 3d space. The graphic drivers on a device cannot determine which  object is closer or farther from the viewpoint since they were in exactly the same place. If we consider reality to be a continuum including our physical and digital experiences, z-fighting is a strictly digital phenomenon as objects trying to occupy the same physical space usually have tragic or intimate consequences.

The work in the current generative art movement is based on deterministic algorithms. This means that given a set of input parameters, the result should be exactly the same. This ideal is hardly ever the case as the code behind the art goes through different processing steps, on different CPUs, rendered on different GPUs, and interpreted by different graphics drivers. The code in this project is deterministic, it includes no conditions to adapt one way or the other to any particular hardware device, yet due to how the varying hardware and software devices try to mitigate z-fighting, this same code generates an entirely different experience on different devices.

To further exploit the nuances of these consequences, this work generates an audio score based on the generated graphics, analysing the canvas with a clustering algorithm and converting color values to notes, volume, and distortion.

A back-end system has been developed to render out each iteration across a variety of devices. To explore this catalog, please visit: 
https://fraguada.net/svsc/

More information about the project in the fx(text) article:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/serendipity-vs-consequence

Slowly developed between May 2022 and March 2023.

~interacting~

click or tap on the artwork canvas to enable audio. audio starts a few seconds after initiating the work.

~ui~
double click or double tap to open the project ui

‚§° - toggle fullscreen
img - save png. please wait for the capture to complete
vid - save webm. saves a 34 second clip with audio

~console~
open the development console on desktop browser for more information on the iteration

The console includes more information about a particular iteration, including parameter values, palette information, and information on some url params you can play with.
Once the audio starts, you can also see an audio score as coloured bars.

~acknowledgements~

To my family and friends for allowing me time and giving me support throughout the development of this project.

~license~

This artwork would not be possible without the collective efforts of many individuals developing open source software. 

three.js, tone.js, RecordRTC, chroma.js, skmeans, html2canvas, file-saver, ua-parser.js

metadata.name: Everything #13
metadata.description:
The slow moving shapes of ‚ÄòEverything‚Äô explore how intricate compositions of space yield to the simple and fluid passage of time. Our human desire, and subsequent failure, to control the infinite expanse of time is our paradoxical reminder that we‚Äôre never actually Done - a delightful reality for those willing to focus on observing the unfolding present. This perpetual motion of time can also help us witness the underlying sameness of all things ‚Äì that absence is form, artificial is reality, chemical is organic, and that the wildly natural is precisely mathematical. Where each piece is part of another piece, everything is everything.

Even something as singular and technical as a pixel, is actually just the assembly of organic matter by humans into something that‚Äôs made to reflect the reality we want to see and share. Is the glowing movement of our screens actually so foreign to the analog mechanics of yesteryear and the hand-made crafts of our ancestors ‚Äì or is it simply another mode of transcending the energies that come to us in an infinite faucet, flowing with beautiful intuitions and knowings for us to create with?

So let‚Äôs flow between colors and dimensional layers, vibes and astral planes, and the idiosyncrasies of endlessly undulating shapes that feel chemical and technical ‚Äì microscopic, of the earth, and of the cosmos ‚Äì an amalgam of matter evolving throughout unfolding time and the overlapping infinite.

------

Intended to be viewed as an animated piece, please tap the play button if you are seeing a cached static image.

Commands in live mode:

P : Play/Pause
S : Save PNG (3000x3600)
F : Enter Fullscreen
Spacebar : Scene Change

URL Parameters:

By default, fullscreen mode will render with a pixel density of 3. This requires a pretty modern gpu for smooth animation. If you are having problems you can lower the density by adding this to the url (without the quotes): ‚Äú&fullscreen=2‚Äù

When not in fullscreen mode, you can also specify a width for the image, in case you want to print something at a higher resolution. Because this is using shaders, the current maximum is around 5000 px, even though you can specify higher numbers. If browsers/GPUs support higher resolutions in the future, then this may change. To set the width, append this to the url: ‚Äú&width=5000‚Äù

Note: To view fullscreen on FireFox, please use the url param and not the ‚ÄúF‚Äù command for best results.

metadata.name: Monochrome Intersections #53
metadata.description:
I decided to do this version because Intersections created too many issues with the previews. I made a reserve list for all collectors of Intersections (this reserve list will be available during 1 week). I put a small price because of preview‚Äôs issues and I am really grateful to saw all my projects found collectors, and I don‚Äôt know how to tell you üôè
‚Ä®I also worked on a bug to fix the rendering on objkt.com.‚Ä®

Monochrome Intersections are a group of artworks creating organic and animated lines. A mix between digital renderings with colorful lines and a generated grid creating a paper-like visual.

Lines are animated with an infinite algorithm to create a mesmerizing animation. 
The pieces's size, position and frequency are generated for each token, along with the colour theme and the composition effect. 

You can click to play/pause the animation.

Features :
- Clip: triangle, circle or reversed triangle
- LinesCount: number of lines
- smallLines: boolean, if lines are thin or bold
- colorTheme: name of the color theme
- filter: Canvas composition effect applied : difference, multiply, xor, hard-light, source-over
- isDistorted: distortions enabled

‚Ä®Handmade by code with Javascript, made with fragment.tools
Quentin Hocd√©, Brussels (Belgium), 2023.

metadata.name: Oxygen #11
metadata.description:
Oxygen makes strange forms of life thrive even in the darkest of places.

This is a generative piece using curated randomness to create textures, generate distortion fields, simulate growth and create compositions.

The work is best viewed in high resolution, but due to the time it takes to render, the preview image is capped to only 1000 pixels in height. You can change the resolution by pressing keys

- 'm' for medium  (height=2000px)
- 'l' for large (height=3500px)
- 'x' for extra large (height=5000px) 

outputs. 

Press 's' to save the output as a PNG file.

For even larger outputs, you can open the work in live mode and append the text '?size=10000' to the URL. Here, you can change the number (10000) to the desired height in pixels. 

Please note, that a very high-resolution image may take a very long time to render and some browsers are not able to save the image. However, even a 10000 pixels tall outputs have been generated during testing.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #7
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js
